values:
So I was sitting in my apartment today, and I decided to put the movie Closer into the DVD player.&nbsp; This was a movie that I felt truely defined me as a person and for the longest time I couldn't really put it into words.&nbsp; I think I have a better understanding now of how it is a movie like that can define what I think of myself.&nbsp;&nbsp;
If you haven't seen the movie, I would say you should, it is well done, and artfully rendered, but keep in mind it isn't by any means a happy movie.&nbsp;&nbsp;
So how exactly does this movie come around to defining me.&nbsp; Well on the surface level the film is about adultury, which one could see why that applies.&nbsp; One could argue that the film was an outward manifestation of my feelings about past events in my life.&nbsp; That isn't actually it.&nbsp; But the comparison could certainly be made.&nbsp; No the thing about the movie that I think so tipified me was that any given time I have felt like each of the characters.&nbsp; To some extent I view the movie as a whole, and choose to see each character as a manifestation of one single consciensousness.&nbsp;&nbsp;
So here is why I think I am more able to explain the concept of this movie and my empathy for it.&nbsp; Something about it doesn't apply any longer.&nbsp; Something has changed either in me, or about me I don't know which.&nbsp; I am just not the person who watched this film years ago.&nbsp; Which got me to thinking, if remembering this emotion brings me closer to the person I was when I saw it, what does that mean about the nature of people and change.
People do change, despite what angry skeptics will say.&nbsp; People don't change on purpose though.&nbsp; They change without knowing they did it.&nbsp; What happens to that pervious carnation of the self.&nbsp; I think they still lurk under the surface ready to reappear when the correct circumstances arise, and then bam that person gets a new if temporary lease on life.&nbsp;&nbsp;
As your life moves on more and more of these incarnations are born, some you like and others you don't, but all in all it doesn't matter, because ultimately you will hold dearly to them all and call them forth like an army of your own personal demons to defend you when you feel threatened.
So to bring this full circle, what the hell does this have to do with "Closer", while watching it I felt a sudden and unpleasent reconnection with that incarnation of myself.&nbsp; I didn't like it anymore, and didn't want to be that person any longer, which got me to thinking can I get rid of that persona...
I don't know but I felt it was worthy of asking anyone who still reads.

This entry is the closest I will every come to a servey.&nbsp;&nbsp;

I know that I am an ass-hole.&nbsp; I know that I am friends with ass-holes and I know who those people are.&nbsp; The question I have is why are we friends with ass-holes.&nbsp; This is not the entry to placate me, don't pretend I am not an ass-hole.&nbsp; What I am interested in is why all of you stay friends with me.&nbsp; In particular I want to know from the people who arn't ass-holes but you are all welcome to give input, course the ass-holes probably don't read my journal ... or anyone elses for that matter.&nbsp;&nbsp;

What is it about me that makes you want to be my friend?

To give Joe some credit this is a fairly true statement of me

"When you first meet Dave, you think, he's an ass-hole.&nbsp; Then you get to know Dave better and you think, he's not an ass-hole after all.&nbsp; Then you really get to know Dave and you realize, "He's and ass-hole."

Any just curious
